		<table border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
	
	<tr>
		<th align="left"><a name="28"></a>W1 - Start-up Starter Kit for Today's Marketplace</th>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Tuesday, May 21, 2002, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:30 AM</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">The dream of launching one's own development 
studio is no less alive today than it's ever 
been, but making that dream a reality certainly 
hasn't gotten any easier over the years. 
Arguably, today's marketplace presents the 
greatest number of challenges ever to the 
aspiring, independent game developer. Hear from a 
group of game developers who have flown in the 
face of conventional wisdom and started their own 
companies. Hear their war stories, learn from 
their mistakes, and, using the experience of 
those who have been there, gauge your potential 
return on investment.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Location:</b> 411 - Theater</td>
	</tr>
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Moderator:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Jeff Green,&nbsp;Computer Gaming World&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
					
			</td>
		</tr>
	
	
	
	
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Panelist:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Jay Minn,&nbsp;BLAM!&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Ray Muzyka,&nbsp;BioWare&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Brian Reynolds,&nbsp;Big Huge Games&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
					
			</td>
		</tr>
	
	
	

</table>
<br />		
			
		
				
		<table border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
	
	<tr>
		<th align="left"><a name="29"></a>W2 - Designing Games That Teach: An MIT Workshop</th>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Tuesday, May 21, 2002, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:30 AM</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">Computer and video games have emerged as a 
potentially powerful educational medium, yet few 
mainstream products have truly harnessed their 
potential. Researchers in MIT's Program in 
Comparative Media Studies, along with a number of 
the game industry's most respected designers, are 
drawing upon research and real-world models of 
success that may well forge a union of creativity 
and profit for designers, educators, and 
publishers. Hear what the MIT Games-to-Teach 
Project has learned, and participate in a 
workshop that brings together game designers, 
humanists, and educators -- all of whom share the 
common goal of creating stimulating games, new 
markets, and fiscally sound business enterprises.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Location:</b> 404AB</td>
	</tr>
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Moderator:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Kurt Squire,&nbsp;M.I.T.&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
					
			</td>
		</tr>
	
	
	
	
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Panelist:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Doug Church,&nbsp;ION Storm&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Henry Jenkins,&nbsp;M.I.T.&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Brenda Laurel,&nbsp;Art Center College of Design&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Bernice Stafford,&nbsp;Lightspan, Inc.&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
					
			</td>
		</tr>
	
	
	

</table>
<br />		
			
		
				
		<table border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
	
	<tr>
		<th align="left"><a name="30"></a>W3 - A Complete Technology Toolkit for Wireless Game Development</th>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Tuesday, May 21, 2002, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:30 AM</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">This workshop will bring the wireless novice up 
to speed on the significant platforms, languages, 
and operating systems available to those coding 
games targeted for the wireless market. Platforms 
to be addressed will include J2ME, BREW, SMS, 
Palm OS, MS Stinger/Win CE, and WAP. This session 
will outline the various wireless standards that 
exist in the U.S. and other major markets, and 
will provide a working foundation for those who 
are beginning their own wireless game 
development. Special attention will be paid to 
the more mature markets of Japan and Europe, 
where turn-based, email-based, and even quasi-
multiplayer games using IP protocols are the norm.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Location:</b> 406AB</td>
	</tr>
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Moderator:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Eric Goldberg,&nbsp;Crossover Technologies&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
					
			</td>
