<br />		
			
		
				
		<table border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
	
	<tr>
		<th align="left"><a name="36"></a>W9 - Listen to Your Gamers: What Player Metrics is Telling Us</th>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Tuesday, May 21, 2002, 3:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;5:30 PM</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">Still designing your game by the seat of your 
pants? Generating sales and marketing plans just 
on a hunch? The new factor in game design and 
marketing is player metrics -- the science of 
discovering, tracking, and predicting player 
patterns and preferences. Player metrics, a new 
twist on market research, is finding its way into 
all facets of the game-design and publishing 
process. From the beginning of the new product 
development cycle through to the introduction of 
sequels, player metrics will help minimize your 
risk and maximize your sales, help you weed out 
winning concept ideas from the dogs, optimize 
your concept and gameplay, and tell you if your 
marketing plan is generating buzz. This workshop 
will teach you ways to use player-metrics models 
to update the way you design both online and 
traditional games, help you understand how gamers 
think and what they respond to, and guide you in 
the task of solidifying your business model 
through research-driven game-design goals.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#eeeeee"><b>Location:</b> 406AB</td>
	</tr>
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Moderator:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Michael Goodman,&nbsp;The Yankee Group&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
					
			</td>
		</tr>
	
	
	
	
	
		
		<tr>
			<td bgcolor="#eeeeee">
			<p><b>Panelist:&nbsp;</b><br />
		
		
		
		
			  Jeff Anderson,&nbsp;Turbine Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Kevin Bachus,&nbsp;Capital Entertainment Group&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
			  Paul Neurath,&nbsp;Flood Gate Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
			
		
		
		
